00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:46.420
let's talk about the fundamentals
of the operating system.

00:07:46.420 --> 00:07:49.120
When we look at the
server operating system,

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:51.110
there's really two sections.

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:53.980
There's the core operating system,
the Core OS.

00:07:53.980 --> 00:07:58.180
That's mostly the Darwin or the BSD,
the low-level components.

00:07:58.180 --> 00:08:01.840
And then on top of that,
there are a number of services

00:08:01.840 --> 00:08:05.880
that we have built and we
are designing and delivering.

00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:10.920
So I'm going to talk a little bit
about the core server operating system.

00:08:11.330 --> 00:08:14.300
There are six major areas of
the server operating system.

00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:17.700
We have the kernel and
the networking components,

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:20.840
our directory services and
network authentication layer,

00:08:20.840 --> 00:08:23.950
which we've taken normally
as a standalone service,

00:08:23.950 --> 00:08:26.980
and we've dropped that down into
the core of the operating system.

00:08:27.400 --> 00:08:31.160
The libraries, the utilities,
security infrastructures,

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:34.900
which normally would be like just
a service that's a standalone

00:08:34.900 --> 00:08:37.710
service right on the OS,
we build down deep into

00:08:37.710 --> 00:08:41.460
the core of the OS,
and even high availability services.

00:08:44.100 --> 00:08:47.020
So if you look at the kernel,
we continue to innovate on

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:51.440
top of the kernel and the
Darwin architecture that we have.

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:56.190
It's combinations of
various versions of BSD.

00:08:57.690 --> 00:09:00.480
One of the new features that
we're talking about here a lot is

00:09:00.860 --> 00:09:03.150
support for 64-bit applications.

00:09:03.160 --> 00:09:07.750
So within Tiger Server,
we now have the capability of

00:09:07.810 --> 00:09:11.120
running 64-bit applications.

00:09:11.120 --> 00:09:16.300
And this is especially useful for
our server customers who are doing

00:09:16.310 --> 00:09:19.000
lots and lots of number crunching.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:23.520
They've got some very large
numerics that they're dealing with.

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:27.060
They need to hold lots of
data in memory at one time.

00:09:27.690 --> 00:09:32.670
So now we can actually allocate
up to 64 bits of memory,

00:09:32.970 --> 00:09:35.350
and your application can take
advantage of all of that.

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:41.200
On the networking side
of the operating system,

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:45.120
we've got, as Bertrand mentioned in his
presentation earlier today,

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:47.650
this is a BSD-based
networking architecture.

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:51.120
For server use, we have capabilities
like IP multi-homing,

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:55.010
so you can have multiple interfaces,
assign IP addresses to each

00:09:55.150 --> 00:09:57.240
of those various interfaces.

00:09:58.020 --> 00:10:00.280
Jumbo frame supports
for dealing with very,

00:10:00.310 --> 00:10:01.430
very large packets.

00:10:01.510 --> 00:10:07.750
Innovative things like IP over FireWire,
so we can have high bandwidth,

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:09.840
low latency interconnects.

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:15.700
One of the new features we're introducing
for the networking... Thank you.

00:10:18.510 --> 00:10:22.250
in Tiger Server is support
for Ethernet link aggregation.

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:27.340
This is compliant with
the 802.3ad standard.

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:31.290
What this allows you to do is take
multiple Ethernet links and aggregate

00:10:31.400 --> 00:10:36.160
them together so you have increased
overall throughput to the server.

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:57.340
It also gives us network
interface failover.

00:10:57.340 --> 00:10:57.340
So if one of those connections,
those physical connections were

00:10:57.340 --> 00:10:57.340
to get disconnected or break
or something happened to it,

00:10:57.340 --> 00:10:57.340
the link can automatically failover to
another cable or another link aggregate.

00:10:57.520 --> 00:11:00.080
So this can be used with
one Ethernet switch.

00:11:00.240 --> 00:11:02.450
It could be used with
two Ethernet switches.

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:07.840
This is an excellent
feature for X Server G5.

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:11.420
If you look in an X Server G5,
we have two onboard

00:11:11.670 --> 00:11:13.720
gigabit Ethernet ports.

00:11:13.720 --> 00:11:16.880
Now, with the right type of switch,
you'll be able to aggregate those

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:20.780
ports together and get better
overall throughput to your server.

00:11:24.070 --> 00:11:27.380
I mentioned this directory
services architecture that we

00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:30.690
call Open Directory that we've
taken and integrated in to the

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:32.520
core of the operating system.

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:37.250
This is a way of basically
bottlenecking all user account and

00:11:37.250 --> 00:11:43.400
authentication lookup requests,
bottlenecking them down deep into the OS,

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:46.260
so that if you're using one of the
applications that Apple delivered

00:11:46.270 --> 00:11:49.640
or a service that we delivered,
or you're building an application or

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:54.200
you're hosting your own application,
you can be using the same

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:58.630
sets of user account names,
the same sets of passwords that the

00:11:58.630 --> 00:12:00.850
rest of the operating system is using.

00:12:00.880 --> 00:12:04.560
So we build this down
deep into Tiger Server.

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:10.300
Also, the other layer we look at is
the Unix commands and libraries.

00:12:10.300 --> 00:12:12.000
There's lots of updates to these.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.900
We continue to try and keep the
