00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:46.010
What's kind of different in the server
operating system is some of the high

00:12:46.110 --> 00:12:48.600
availability components that we build in.

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:52.960
If you have a server,
you want your server to be reliable.

00:12:52.960 --> 00:12:56.250
You want it to be up and
running seven days a week,

00:12:56.250 --> 00:12:57.800
24 hours a day.

00:12:57.800 --> 00:12:59.340
You don't want it to have any problems.

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:03.140
And if there are problems,
you want your server to do whatever it

00:13:03.140 --> 00:13:07.570
can to try and fix those problems and
not have those problems to begin with.

00:13:07.940 --> 00:13:12.120
So there's some features that we
deliver within the product for this.

00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:14.360
As you know,
on the server operating system,

00:13:14.360 --> 00:13:17.200
we introduced file system
journaling a long time ago.

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:19.950
We have support for
software RAID capabilities.

00:13:19.950 --> 00:13:23.280
Tiger Server, we now have even RAID 10.

00:13:23.280 --> 00:13:25.060
We have auto-restart capabilities.

00:13:25.060 --> 00:13:28.310
So your service, if your service dies,
we can restart your service.

00:13:28.310 --> 00:13:31.150
If there's a problem with the
entire server operating system,

00:13:31.150 --> 00:13:33.780
the hardware can actually
automatically restart.

00:13:35.990 --> 00:13:39.580
One of the features we delivered
a while ago was IP failover.

00:13:39.660 --> 00:13:42.650
And we're introducing a kind of a
next generation of IP failover today,

00:13:42.650 --> 00:13:45.490
and we call it high
availability clustering.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:51.930
What this allows you to do is take
two X Servers that are connected

00:13:51.930 --> 00:13:56.590
to the same shared storage and
have an active/passive failover.

00:13:56.590 --> 00:13:58.900
You can create what we
call a cluster pair.

00:13:58.900 --> 00:14:04.900
And you can create these pairs
and have them do the same thing.

00:14:04.920 --> 00:14:08.890
What we're automating in Tiger Server is
support for network file services.

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:12.690
So your AFP, your SIFs,
your NFS file services,

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:17.880
we're going to automate the
creation of these clustered pairs.

00:14:17.900 --> 00:14:19.900
So you can have two servers.

00:14:19.900 --> 00:14:22.890
If one of those servers were
to fail or was to go down,

00:14:22.970 --> 00:14:27.900
the other server will automatically take
over the responsibilities for that server

00:14:27.900 --> 00:14:30.890
in handling its network file services.

00:14:30.900 --> 00:14:32.880
So this is a great solution.

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:35.900
As you'll hear in a
presentation tomorrow morning,

00:14:36.060 --> 00:14:38.900
there's a really flexible
network file system.

00:14:38.900 --> 00:14:41.050
There's a really flexible
architecture here.

00:14:41.050 --> 00:14:44.900
And you can build your own custom
solutions using this high availability

00:14:44.900 --> 00:14:46.890
clustering architecture that we've built.

