The services layer includes server
administration to make management of all

00:15:30.210 --> 00:15:32.700
the services in Mac OS X Server easy.

00:15:32.800 --> 00:15:36.070
We have directory services to provide
naming and authentication to all the

00:15:36.070 --> 00:15:38.340
servers and clients on the network.

00:15:38.450 --> 00:15:41.440
Cross-platform workgroup
and collaboration services.

00:15:41.590 --> 00:15:45.560
Client management to make management
and deployment of Macintosh

00:15:45.560 --> 00:15:47.900
clients on the network very simple.

00:15:47.990 --> 00:15:49.850
Internet networking services.

00:15:49.970 --> 00:15:53.410
And new Integra server,
we have high-performance

00:15:53.410 --> 00:15:56.020
computing clustering services.

00:15:56.440 --> 00:15:58.940
So first let's talk about
server administration.

00:15:58.960 --> 00:16:03.280
The server administration facilities in
Mac OS X Server integrate all of the many

00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:07.050
open source products that we put into
the server and make it easy to manage.

00:16:07.170 --> 00:16:10.600
We have two main server management
applications in Mac OS X Server.

00:16:10.600 --> 00:16:15.990
Server Admin, which lets you configure,
set up, configure, and monitor all of the

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:18.020
services in Mac OS X Server.

00:16:18.020 --> 00:16:21.650
It also lets you manage multiple
servers from the same console.

00:16:22.710 --> 00:16:25.520
Workgroup Manager is our
directory management application.

00:16:25.540 --> 00:16:28.850
It lets you manage all of the user
and group accounts in the directory.

00:16:28.970 --> 00:16:31.600
It's designed to work
with Open Directory,

00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:33.640
but it does work with any LDAP directory.

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:36.690
It also lets you manage all
of the services that are

00:16:36.800 --> 00:16:40.740
configured out of the directory,
such as preference management

00:16:40.790 --> 00:16:42.540
for client management.

00:16:43.400 --> 00:16:46.640
We're introducing a couple new
management features in Tiger Server,

00:16:46.670 --> 00:16:49.570
the first of which is
access control lists.

00:16:53.410 --> 00:16:55.890
We have several types of
access control lists in

00:16:55.890 --> 00:16:59.960
Tiger Server for the file system,
for services, and for the directory.

00:17:00.070 --> 00:17:03.200
Now, those of you that are familiar
with Panther Server know that

00:17:03.200 --> 00:17:06.030
it uses Unix permissions,
and Unix permissions,

00:17:06.150 --> 00:17:09.190
while they work well in simple cases,
have problems being mapped

00:17:09.190 --> 00:17:10.280
to real-world workflow.

00:17:10.360 --> 00:17:13.510
If you have shared files on the
network and you need to be able to

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:16.450
set up groups of users who can write
to those files and other groups

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:18.950
of users who can only read them,
it's not really possible to

00:17:18.950 --> 00:17:20.630
specify that with Unix permissions.

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:23.450
So we have full support for
access control lists in the file

00:17:23.450 --> 00:17:26.620
system to provide fine-grained
control over those objects.

00:17:26.690 --> 00:17:29.710
We also support other common
features that you would expect

00:17:29.710 --> 00:17:32.780
from access control lists,
like groups within groups and full

00:17:32.780 --> 00:17:36.130
lists of users and groups that can be
assigned to the file system objects.

00:17:36.220 --> 00:17:39.610
You can specify inheritance for the ACLs.

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:40.280
And you can specify the access control
list for the file system objects.

00:17:40.360 --> 00:17:43.350
You can also have control over the
default permissions of objects that

00:17:43.390 --> 00:17:44.940
are created in the file system.

00:17:46.270 --> 00:17:49.780
Now another area that can be difficult
in working with file systems and

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:53.630
different permissions models is being
able to work compatibly across multiple

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:55.500
different types of file systems.

00:17:55.590 --> 00:17:59.040
But because we support all of
the features such as inheritance,

00:17:59.040 --> 00:18:02.340
default permissions,
fine-grain permission settings,

00:18:02.340 --> 00:18:06.020
and allow and deny rules,
Mac OS X Server and Mac OS X can be

00:18:06.070 --> 00:18:10.500
made to work in a compatible manner
with Windows Server and with Windows XP.

00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:15.690
So it simplifies working in
a cross-platform environment.

00:18:16.960 --> 00:18:20.480
We have other access
control in Mac OS X server,

00:18:20.480 --> 00:18:21.500
another area of service.

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:25.520
In Mac OS X server today,
if you have a server bound to a

00:18:25.600 --> 00:18:28.990
directory that has thousands or
even tens of thousands of users

00:18:29.070 --> 00:18:32.630
and you set up a file server,
for instance, every user account in that

00:18:32.770 --> 00:18:34.820
directory can log onto the server.

00:18:34.820 --> 00:18:38.380
Now, you can control permissions,
file system's permissions to

00:18:38.380 --> 00:18:41.150
ensure that only the correct
users get access to your data,

00:18:41.420 --> 00:18:44.660
but in many cases you want to restrict
that only to a core set of users.

00:18:45.150 --> 00:18:48.490
And with Tiger Server,
we're introducing service ACLs so

00:18:48.490 --> 00:18:52.220
that every user-based service in the
server can control the set of users

00:18:52.250 --> 00:18:54.390
and groups that can access the server.

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:57.260
You can have the same list for
all services on your server or

00:18:57.260 --> 00:18:58.780
energy server independently.

00:18:58.780 --> 00:19:00.190
So that's service ACLs.

00:19:00.220 --> 00:19:02.780
And finally,
we have directory ACLs which are

00:19:02.830 --> 00:19:06.250
global ACLs that allow you to
control who can access and update

00:19:06.250 --> 00:19:08.160
the contents of open directory.

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:11.620
And something that open directory
does different from other LDAP servers

00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:15.280
is it stores these directory
ACLs in the directory itself

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:18.900
to allow them to be propagated
to the replicas by taking advantage

00:19:18.910 --> 00:19:20.630
of open directory's replication.

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:23.540
So that's access control
lists in Tiger Server.

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:31.640
Another new feature we have for
management in Tiger Server is

00:19:31.640 --> 00:19:33.100
certificate management.

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:36.720
Now certificate management in X3
involved going into the command

00:19:36.720 --> 00:19:39.720
line and it was different for each
service and although it could be done,

00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:41.600
it was sometimes somewhat cumbersome.

00:19:41.710 --> 00:19:44.540
So we've simplified this
greatly in Tiger Server.

00:19:44.630 --> 00:19:48.540
We've added certificate management in
the administration tools and you can

00:19:48.540 --> 00:19:52.340
use this with certificates that are
signed by certificate authorities.

00:19:52.440 --> 00:19:55.770
And you can also use Tiger's
new certificate assistant

00:19:55.770 --> 00:19:59.990
for self-signing your own
certificates in your organization.

00:20:00.100 --> 00:20:03.200
You can display all the certificates
you have available and assign them

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:05.080
to services or websites as necessary.

00:20:05.160 --> 00:20:08.690
So that's certificate
management in Tiger Server.

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:16.630
Next up, we'll talk about Open Directory.

00:20:16.740 --> 00:20:20.000
Open Directory is Apple's
directory and naming service.

00:20:20.150 --> 00:20:23.890
It's standards-based,
and it implements LDAP naming services,

00:20:24.030 --> 00:20:27.130
and it implements Kerberos
for authentication.

00:20:28.170 --> 00:20:32.230
We use OpenLDAP and MIT Kerberos.

00:20:32.460 --> 00:20:34.300
Kerberos is used to
implement single sign-on,

00:20:34.300 --> 00:20:36.550
which lets you log in
once with one password.

00:20:36.730 --> 00:20:38.020
It's never sent over the network.

00:20:38.070 --> 00:20:41.880
And you get an authentication ticket,
which is good for all

00:20:41.900 --> 00:20:43.110
services in Mac OS X.

00:20:43.460 --> 00:20:46.330
We also have a support for what
we call the password server,

00:20:46.330 --> 00:20:49.000
which supports password
replication to all of the open

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.010
directory replicas on the network.

00:20:51.060 --> 00:20:54.400
And this includes replicating all
of the Kerberos support as well,

00:20:54.450 --> 00:20:57.260
so that you can have replicated
Kerberos authentication

00:20:57.260 --> 00:20:58.870
across your entire network.

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:00.940
We integrate Samba.

00:21:02.410 --> 00:21:05.560
With Open Directory as well to
provide MT domain services for

00:21:05.560 --> 00:21:08.520
your Windows clients to allow
them to authenticate as well with

00:21:08.520 --> 00:21:10.350
the same account information.

00:21:10.440 --> 00:21:12.850
And of course,
we mentioned all the replication

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:14.580
that's built into Open Directory.

00:21:15.100 --> 00:21:17.260
We have a couple enhancements
that we're putting into

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:18.840
Open Directory in Tiger Server.

00:21:18.840 --> 00:21:20.800
The first is managed network browsing.

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:21.660
Now, what is this?

00:21:21.660 --> 00:21:24.780
In 10.3 today,
if you have a large organization

00:21:24.780 --> 00:21:27.830
and you go to network,
it can get somewhat confusing and

00:21:27.830 --> 00:21:31.660
unwieldy and difficult to navigate,
and we fixed that in Tiger and

00:21:31.660 --> 00:21:35.900
Tiger Server by allowing you to control
the contents of the network directory,

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:38.780
and you can see you can greatly simplify
it and make it easy to navigate.

00:21:39.160 --> 00:21:41.920
We provide virtual network views,
which can be controlled by

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:43.460
the network administrator.

00:21:43.460 --> 00:21:46.390
The view is defined in
the Mac OS X Server,

00:21:46.390 --> 00:21:50.020
and it's stored in the directory,
so any client that binds to

00:21:50.020 --> 00:21:51.620
Open Directory will see the view.

00:21:51.620 --> 00:21:55.570
You can combine both dynamic service
discovery protocols for Mac and Windows,

00:21:55.570 --> 00:21:58.520
as well as static entries that
are stored in the directory,

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:01.660
and you can even have pointers
to other entries that are outside

00:22:01.660 --> 00:22:04.760
of your local network that
show up in the network folder.

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:06.920
And we make it easy to manage.

00:22:06.960 --> 00:22:08.380
It's managed through WorkRoot Manager.

00:22:09.160 --> 00:22:11.980
Our directory management tool,
where you can create these

00:22:11.980 --> 00:22:13.270
views and preview them.

00:22:13.280 --> 00:22:16.460
So this greatly simplifies and
makes it easier to set up the

00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:20.280
network folder in your clients
in Mac OS X Server and in Tiger.

00:22:21.710 --> 00:22:26.910
We've also made some
enhancements to Open Directory.

00:22:28.100 --> 00:22:30.800
Some of which include, as we mentioned,
storage of the access

00:22:30.830 --> 00:22:32.200
controls in the directory.

00:22:32.200 --> 00:22:34.990
Another thing that we're storing in the
directory itself is the LDAP schema.

00:22:35.060 --> 00:22:37.650
So the schema will now be
propagated to replicas as well as

00:22:37.650 --> 00:22:39.220
the access control information.

00:22:39.270 --> 00:22:42.120
So again,
this greatly simplifies managing

00:22:42.120 --> 00:22:47.170
multiple open directory servers and
simplifies the replication process.

00:22:47.460 --> 00:22:50.430
We're adding organizational unit
support so you can have multiple

00:22:50.430 --> 00:22:54.720
independent LDAP data sets hosted
out of your open directory server.

00:22:54.770 --> 00:22:56.150
We're improving the scalability.

00:22:56.240 --> 00:23:00.760
We've tested up to 200,000 servers,
200,000 records per server.

00:23:00.810 --> 00:23:04.420
And we've added some tools that
really help simplify the process of

00:23:04.420 --> 00:23:06.900
managing large open directory services.

00:23:07.030 --> 00:23:10.480
We've improved search and apply so
you can do batch editing of large

00:23:10.480 --> 00:23:14.480
number of records in the server as
well as improving the import tools.

00:23:14.540 --> 00:23:17.300
And additionally,
since you need to back up all this data,

00:23:17.300 --> 00:23:20.520
we've built in hot backup command
line utilities that allow you

00:23:20.520 --> 00:23:25.790
to back up your naming and
authentication database on the fly.

00:23:27.340 --> 00:23:29.830
And we've made some
enhancements to security.

00:23:29.830 --> 00:23:32.560
We have authenticated directory
binding in the server and the

00:23:32.560 --> 00:23:36.000
client so that administrators can
control who accesses the directory

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:39.200
and you have mutual authentication
between the client and server.

00:23:39.370 --> 00:23:45.150
And we have the NTLMv2 authentication for
Windows clients to provide more security

00:23:45.150 --> 00:23:47.990
for Windows client authentication.

00:23:49.740 --> 00:23:52.060
Another area of services
in Mac OS X Server is

00:23:52.060 --> 00:23:54.000
workgroup and collaboration.

00:23:54.030 --> 00:23:58.400
Workgroup and collaboration services
provide for sharing in workgroups,

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:01.530
and the most common of these, obviously,
are file and print.

00:24:01.650 --> 00:24:05.140
And like we do today, we support file and
print sharing for Mac,

00:24:05.150 --> 00:24:06.960
Windows, and Linux clients.

00:24:07.100 --> 00:24:10.670
This works for folders on the
file server as well as home

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:15.030
directories between Mac and Windows,
and sharing your network

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:16.920
printers as well,
so all of your local workgroup resources.

00:24:17.120 --> 00:24:19.770
These are fully integrated
in Mac OS X Server.

00:24:20.070 --> 00:24:23.020
All of the protocols can
share the same SharePoint,

00:24:23.130 --> 00:24:24.590
the same shared folders.

00:24:24.680 --> 00:24:27.480
They use the same access privileges,
the same account information,

00:24:27.500 --> 00:24:31.040
so you set it up once and the files
are accessible from all clients.

00:24:31.040 --> 00:24:33.870
The Windows domain services
are integrated as well,

00:24:33.940 --> 00:24:38.260
so the Windows clients have full access
to all of the resources on the server.

00:24:38.260 --> 00:24:41.660
We support Windows roaming
profile for home directory logins,

00:24:41.660 --> 00:24:45.750
and we have native print services
for both Mac and Windows clients.

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:52.000
We made some enhancements
to work of services as well.

00:24:52.100 --> 00:24:54.300
Couple of these are unified file locks.

00:24:54.300 --> 00:24:57.700
Now we have file locking
today in Mac OS X Server,

00:24:57.780 --> 00:25:01.680
but we've enhanced this to make sure that
the file locking is consistent between

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:05.100
all the protocols so that no matter
what client you're logging in from,

00:25:05.100 --> 00:25:07.770
no matter what platform,
if you're accessing the same

00:25:07.770 --> 00:25:09.680
data you get consistent locking.

00:25:09.760 --> 00:25:11.710
We've added --

00:25:13.060 --> 00:25:16.150
We've added backup domain
controller support,

00:25:16.150 --> 00:25:19.800
which exists today in Samba,
but we've added configuration for this

00:25:19.800 --> 00:25:23.320
and then management tools to make it
easy to set up to provide read-only

00:25:23.320 --> 00:25:26.400
failover for the Windows domain
services for greater reliability.

00:25:26.400 --> 00:25:30.340
And we've integrated the print
services more directly with

00:25:30.420 --> 00:25:34.880
CUPS so that when you manage print
services in Server Admin now,

00:25:34.880 --> 00:25:38.420
you are managing the CUPS queues,
you're managing the CUPS printing.

00:25:38.580 --> 00:25:41.620
We've eliminated some of the middle
layers there and really had tighter

00:25:41.640 --> 00:25:43.620
integration in print services with CUPS.

00:25:43.620 --> 00:25:46.480
And we've also added print
authentication so you can

00:25:46.480 --> 00:25:48.440
control access to print queues.

00:25:51.910 --> 00:25:54.890
We've added a few new services for
work group and collaboration as well.

00:25:54.910 --> 00:25:56.800
The first is the iChat server.

00:25:56.890 --> 00:26:00.920
The Tiger iChat server provides
encrypted messaging for your

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:03.200
intranet and a secure namespace.

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:07.080
It's based on Jabber
using the XMPP protocol.

00:26:07.140 --> 00:26:10.790
And it provides cross-platform support,
obviously with Jabber clients

00:26:10.820 --> 00:26:12.660
as well as Tiger's iChat client.

00:26:12.660 --> 00:26:16.120
And because it's integrated
with Open Directory,

00:26:16.120 --> 00:26:20.910
it provides a secure namespace for
chat within your local intranet.

00:26:25.900 --> 00:26:30.350
We also have a weblog server that we're
introducing in TigerServer as well.

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:34.490
A weblog is a way of easily
publishing and syndicating

00:26:34.490 --> 00:26:35.900
information on the internet.

00:26:35.900 --> 00:26:40.510
And what the weblog server does is
allow you to publish information

00:26:40.510 --> 00:26:44.900
and syndicate it using standard
protocols like RSS or Atom.

00:26:44.900 --> 00:26:46.900
This morning you heard about Safari SSS.

00:26:46.900 --> 00:26:50.820
Our weblog server is completely
compatible with Safari SSS as well

00:26:50.820 --> 00:26:52.900
as any other popular RSS reader.

00:26:52.900 --> 00:26:56.800
We have a number of features that
we support around style sheets

00:26:56.830 --> 00:27:01.200
and calendar-based navigation
that people who manage weblogs can

00:27:01.200 --> 00:27:02.900
control for their individual log.

00:27:02.900 --> 00:27:07.070
The logs themselves are automatically
created as needed for user

00:27:07.080 --> 00:27:08.900
accounts in Open Directory.

00:27:08.930 --> 00:27:13.820
And you can post to them directly from
the web or from clients that support

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.890
standard protocols like XMLRPC or Atom.

00:27:16.900 --> 00:27:18.710
And another feature we have in
Mac OS X Server and TigerServer is

00:27:18.710 --> 00:27:19.800
the ability to have group weblogs.

00:27:19.930 --> 00:27:20.980
Eric Zelenk,
Greg Burns We have a number of

00:27:20.980 --> 00:27:21.370
features that we support around style
sheets and calendar-based navigation

00:27:21.390 --> 00:27:21.900
that people who manage weblogs
can control for their individual log.

00:27:21.900 --> 00:27:22.520
The logs themselves are automatically
created as needed for user

00:27:22.580 --> 00:27:22.900
accounts in Open Directory.

00:27:22.900 --> 00:27:25.900
as well so that people that are
doing shared project weblogs

00:27:25.900 --> 00:27:30.510
can use a group account in
Open Directory to have multiple

00:27:30.510 --> 00:27:33.480
folks have right access to a weblog.

00:27:33.710 --> 00:27:36.790
So now I'd like to have Eric come
up again and do a quick demo of

00:27:36.790 --> 00:27:39.610
Weblog Services and Tiger Server.

00:27:42.900 --> 00:27:44.800
Thank you, Greg.

00:27:44.800 --> 00:27:47.440
So the Weblog server that we've
built into Tiger Server is

00:27:47.440 --> 00:27:48.970
going to be a wonderful tool.

00:27:48.970 --> 00:27:51.800
It's going to allow people to
better syndicate or publish

00:27:51.800 --> 00:27:54.960
their content out to others,
but also allow a new way for

00:27:54.960 --> 00:27:57.720
groups to communicate information.

00:27:57.940 --> 00:28:01.530
I think one of the benefits of
RSS and syndication of information

00:28:01.550 --> 00:28:05.410
is it makes it really easy to
communicate with the rest of the world.

00:28:05.450 --> 00:28:08.660
Part of the problem with it is
how do I get that information

00:28:08.660 --> 00:28:10.330
out to the rest of the world?

00:28:10.330 --> 00:28:12.480
How can I publish this information?

00:28:12.480 --> 00:28:15.480
I'm not an XML expert,
so how can I create this data and

00:28:15.480 --> 00:28:17.980
push it out to the rest of the world?

00:28:17.980 --> 00:28:21.060
So let me show you how easy that
is going to be in Tiger Server.

00:28:21.100 --> 00:28:24.560
First of all, I'm going to launch the
server admin application.

00:28:24.560 --> 00:28:27.200
Server admin application here.

00:28:27.200 --> 00:28:27.870
I'm going to go to Tiger Server.

00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:30.930
I'm going to go in and
enter for the web server.

00:28:30.940 --> 00:28:32.660
It's very, very simple.

00:28:32.660 --> 00:28:36.720
I can go to the site that I'm hosting,
and with a simple checkbox,

00:28:36.860 --> 00:28:39.120
I can enable the Weblog server.

00:28:40.920 --> 00:28:45.790
Next, let's go down to Safari.

00:28:46.970 --> 00:28:46.970
And I'll open up Safari here.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.560
Okay, let me log back in.

00:28:49.560 --> 00:28:53.800
So I've connected off to the
weblog server which is running

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:56.480
on this Tiger server box here.

00:28:56.480 --> 00:28:58.070
You'll notice a couple things.

00:28:58.090 --> 00:29:01.060
