00:32:09.380 --> 00:32:11.400
Now let's move on to Client Management.

00:32:11.490 --> 00:32:14.400
Client Management Services in
Mac OS X Server let you

00:32:14.400 --> 00:32:18.300
easily deploy and manage large
numbers of Macintosh computers.

00:32:18.300 --> 00:32:22.350
We have Client Management Services that
let you control preferences

00:32:22.350 --> 00:32:23.740
and capabilities on the client.

00:32:23.790 --> 00:32:25.870
This is called
Directory-Based Management,

00:32:25.870 --> 00:32:27.290
or Preference Management.

00:32:27.300 --> 00:32:31.530
This is deployed via Open Directory,
and it's configured from the Workgroup

00:32:31.530 --> 00:32:33.400
Manager application in Mac OS X Server.

00:32:34.330 --> 00:32:37.370
We also have System Imaging
Services that make it easy to

00:32:37.370 --> 00:32:44.100
set up and deploy software on
systems throughout your network.

00:32:44.100 --> 00:32:44.100
NetBoot lets you

00:32:44.120 --> 00:32:47.530
configure a single image or a
small group of image and boot

00:32:47.530 --> 00:32:49.440
network systems from the server.

00:32:49.440 --> 00:32:52.830
You can also use NetInstall to
install those same images to systems

00:32:52.900 --> 00:32:54.670
that are on the network as well.

00:32:54.680 --> 00:32:58.600
We've made a few improvements to
system imaging in Tiger Server,

00:32:58.600 --> 00:33:00.960
the first of which is when
you create these images,

00:33:00.960 --> 00:33:04.330
we now configure the open directory
configuration for your network in the

00:33:04.330 --> 00:33:07.070
images to make it easier to deploy
the images without having to tweak

00:33:07.090 --> 00:33:08.800
open directory settings afterwards.

00:33:08.800 --> 00:33:13.480
We also are supporting block copy for
software installs and NetInstalls to

00:33:13.490 --> 00:33:16.670
greatly speed the net install process.

00:33:19.080 --> 00:33:21.520
And lastly,
we're allowing you to create bootable

00:33:21.530 --> 00:33:25.010
DVD images from your NetInstall images.

00:33:27.100 --> 00:33:30.200
So you can install those images
on systems that are offline,

00:33:30.230 --> 00:33:32.660
off the network.

00:33:32.670 --> 00:33:35.060
We have a few other services
that we're adding to client

00:33:35.060 --> 00:33:37.980
management in Tiger Server,
the first of which is

00:33:37.980 --> 00:33:39.560
mobile home directories.

00:33:39.580 --> 00:33:42.570
Mobile home directories
lets you take user files,

00:33:42.570 --> 00:33:45.840
accounts,
and other information that pertains to

00:33:45.940 --> 00:33:51.060
your home directory and sync it between
a portable and a network home directory.

00:33:51.110 --> 00:33:54.810
This synchronization occurs when the
portable is connected to the network.

00:33:54.810 --> 00:33:57.080
It occurs in the background
with trickle sync.

00:33:57.080 --> 00:33:59.690
And when your portable is offline
and these files are updated,

00:33:59.690 --> 00:34:02.320
the files in your home directory
and your document folder,

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:05.240
your preferences, and they're updated,
when you connect back to the

00:34:05.250 --> 00:34:08.680
network to the home directory,
they'll be synced back up to the server.

00:34:08.680 --> 00:34:12.420
So this allows you to maintain consistent
information between your portable and

00:34:12.420 --> 00:34:15.960
your network home directory server,
and it also allows you to have a backup

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:21.280
of the contents of the portable on the
network in case it ever becomes lost.

00:34:21.280 --> 00:34:24.240
And because the account information
is synchronized as well between the

00:34:24.240 --> 00:34:27.690
portable computer and the network,
the single sign-on on the network is

00:34:27.690 --> 00:34:30.940
also brought down to the portable when
it's offline because all of the account

00:34:30.940 --> 00:34:34.960
information and the authentication
information is synchronized as well.

00:34:34.960 --> 00:34:37.100
So that's mobile home
directories in Tiger Server.

00:34:43.200 --> 00:34:46.840
And Software Update Server,
we heard in the earlier session,

00:34:46.870 --> 00:34:50.430
allows you to

00:34:50.740 --> 00:34:55.420
Deal with an issue that we have today
where we have a lot of software updates

00:34:55.480 --> 00:35:00.340
that make it very easy to maintain the
latest software on your Mac OS X systems.

00:35:00.340 --> 00:35:01.500
It makes it very convenient.

00:35:01.500 --> 00:35:05.950
But when we have a new update like
a Mac OS X 10.10.3.4 and you have

00:35:06.330 --> 00:35:10.540
everyone in your organization downloading
that update the day it comes out,

00:35:10.540 --> 00:35:13.610
it can create a real strain
on your network bandwidth.

00:35:13.620 --> 00:35:17.860
So software update allows you to
use Mac OS X's software updates,

00:35:17.860 --> 00:35:22.930
but by providing a proxy cache server for
software updates also conserves network

00:35:23.040 --> 00:35:26.720
bandwidth and makes it easier for you to
get those updates into your organization.

00:35:26.720 --> 00:35:29.320
It's totally transparent and automatic.

00:35:29.320 --> 00:35:33.470
When software updates become available,
they're downloaded to the server

00:35:33.470 --> 00:35:35.560
and made available to the clients.

00:35:35.560 --> 00:35:37.110
But you have control as well.

00:35:37.110 --> 00:35:40.600
Some sites like to test the
updates to make sure it works

00:35:40.600 --> 00:35:42.840
with their internal software.

00:35:42.840 --> 00:35:43.300
Before they're downloaded,
they're going to have to go

00:35:43.320 --> 00:35:43.600
through a lot of testing.

00:35:43.600 --> 00:35:45.980
How do they make them
available for deployment?

00:35:45.980 --> 00:35:50.180
And so you can either choose to make the
software updates automatically available

00:35:50.190 --> 00:35:55.150
to clients as soon as they're posted,
or you can make that step manual and test

00:35:55.150 --> 00:35:58.990
the updates yourself and then release
them once you're satisfied that they

00:35:59.090 --> 00:36:00.940
work with your internal applications.

00:36:00.940 --> 00:36:02.700
Software update server.

00:36:09.890 --> 00:36:13.720
Internet and networking services
in Mac OS X Server allow you

00:36:13.720 --> 00:36:17.370
to manage your network and host
applications such as web services,

00:36:17.440 --> 00:36:19.800
mail, and Java application services.

00:36:19.800 --> 00:36:22.910
For networking support
in Mac OS X Server,

00:36:22.910 --> 00:36:26.800
we support DNS for domain
address name management,

00:36:26.800 --> 00:36:32.000
DHCP for IP address assignments,
NAT for connecting to the Internet and

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:34.800
for sharing IP addresses among systems.

00:36:34.800 --> 00:36:37.800
We support firewall for securing
your connection to the Internet,

00:36:37.800 --> 00:36:40.040
and we support VPN to
allow remote clients,

00:36:40.090 --> 00:36:44.460
whether they be Mac or Windows,
to access the services on your network

00:36:44.460 --> 00:36:47.040
securely from a remote location.

00:36:47.690 --> 00:36:51.770
We've made a few enhancements to
networking services in Tiger Server.

00:36:51.870 --> 00:36:53.620
The first is site-to-site VPN.

00:36:53.790 --> 00:36:57.180
If you have multiple sites and
you want to have a secure LAN,

00:36:57.300 --> 00:36:59.870
virtual LAN between them,
we now allow you to set up

00:36:59.870 --> 00:37:02.360
site-to-site VPN between these sites.

00:37:02.360 --> 00:37:05.630
We do this over the internet
securely with IPSec.

00:37:05.900 --> 00:37:09.990
We've improved server management
with DHCP by allowing you to manage

00:37:09.990 --> 00:37:14.000
systems that have multiple network
interfaces and handled address

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:17.900
assignment for those systems,
as well as handling static IP address

00:37:17.900 --> 00:37:19.650
assignment in server admin as well.

00:37:19.660 --> 00:37:22.910
And we've improved the
workflow for DNS management.

00:37:22.910 --> 00:37:26.890
We've greatly simplified
that over the 10.3 release.

00:37:27.550 --> 00:37:31.500
Another area of networking services
that can be somewhat difficult is

00:37:31.500 --> 00:37:34.210
setting up internet gateway services.

00:37:34.330 --> 00:37:35.840
This is fairly complex.

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:38.500
There are a number of services
that all have to be configured

00:37:38.620 --> 00:37:40.310
consistently with each other.

00:37:40.310 --> 00:37:42.560
And we've simplified this
in Tiger Server through the

00:37:42.560 --> 00:37:43.780
Gateway Setup Assistant.

00:37:43.780 --> 00:37:47.500
This sets up everything you
need for an internet gateway.

00:37:47.500 --> 00:37:50.860
So it configures your DHCP and
your VPN address ranges,

00:37:50.860 --> 00:37:53.330
NAT port routing, the firewall VPN.

00:37:53.340 --> 00:37:55.910
And it does it in just
a few simple steps.

00:37:55.960 --> 00:37:59.360
And so this is ideal for small sites,
small businesses that have a

00:37:59.360 --> 00:38:02.480
connection to the internet,
for remote sites that share one

00:38:02.480 --> 00:38:03.480
DSL connection to the internet.

00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:07.480
It makes it very easy to set up
the server as an internet gateway.

00:38:07.480 --> 00:38:10.250
So I'm going to ask Eric to
come up again and demo this

00:38:10.250 --> 00:38:13.060
and show you how simple it is.

